commitResults.messageTitle: Merge branch 'branch-Level-10'
Fix JavaDoc comments to follow coding standard
commitResults.messageBody:
Some JavaDoc comments violate the course Java coding
standard. The most common error is that some method headers do not
start with a verb in singular form (such as "Add" instead of "Adds").
This means that the JavaDoc comments don't follow a consistent style.

Following the coding standard helps improve code quality.

Let's change the JavaDoc comments to fix these issues and
follow the coding standard.

Refer to the following link for course coding standard for JavaDoc
comments:
https://se-education.org/guides/conventions/java/index.html#comments

commitResults.messageTitle: Output File I/O error message via GUI instead of System.out
commitResults.messageBody:
The error message when updating task list changes to save disk is
displayed via System.out instead of the GUI.

As we transition to a GUI app, user is unlikely to monitor the
standard output. Thus, user may miss the error message.

Let's change the File I/O error message to be shown as a bot
message in the JavaFX GUI.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove unused methods
Merge branch 'branch-Level-10'
Comment to explain why some classes override equals and hashCode
commitResults.messageBody:
All non-singleton subclasses of UserCommand override Object#equals()
and Object#hashCode().

It may not be obvious why overriding these methods is necessary,
since the software appears to never need to check equality of
command objects, nor does it ever use commands in collections
like HashMap. Thus, a future contributor may remove these methods.

Let's add comments to explain why these methods are overridden.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove unused toString() implementation
Delete dead code
Use polymorphism to shorten handleInputAndGetOutput method
commitResults.messageBody:
The IttyBotty::handleInputAndGetOutput() method is very long. This is
mainly due to handling different UserCommand subtypes using if-else if
instanceof checks.

Long methods make it harder for readers to process and find errors.

Let's use polymorphism to extract a common UserCommand method
to shorten this method.

Using polymorphism allows us to elegantly handle different command
types and expand easily when new command types are added.
